h>\n      <th>prompt_coverage</th>\n      <th>mean_success_prob</th>\n      <th>train_examples</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n</div>"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":14},{"id":"b648a2b7","cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n## 6. Reading the outcomes\n\nThe experiment can produce several scientifically distinct results.\n\n### A. The on-policy rule generalizes\n\nAt matched target accuracy,\n\n\\[\nF_{\\text{on-policy}}(g) < F_{\\text{SFT}}(g)\n\\]\n\nin both the supported and novel settings. This would strengthen the claim beyond the original benchmark suite and show that verified self-generated trajectories retain an advantage even for arbitrary new mappings.\n\n### B. The rule is support-conditional\n\nIterative on-policy SFT works in the supported task but cannot gather enough verified trajectories in the novel task. The mixed method succeeds by first importing support from demonstrations and then switching on-policy.\n\nThis supports the sharper rule:\n\n> On-policy learning is retention-friendly when the desired behavior is already reachable; external supervision is needed for mode creation.\n\n### C. On-policy data is insufficient\n\nIterative on-policy SFT reaches the new target but forgets as much as or more than offline SFT at matched target gain. This directly falsifies the universal claim that on-policy data itself is the primary stabilizer.\n\n### D. Conflict defeats retention\n\nIn the direct-conflict setting, old and new performance cannot both be perfect because the same prompt is assigned two incompatible labels. Failure here is not evidence that one optimizer is poor; it demonstrates that no universal continual-learning rule can ignore task compatibility.\n\n## 7. Necessary extensions before publication\n\nFor a publishable result, repeat with:\n\n- at least three seeds;\n- Qwen2.5-1.5B-Instruct or a 3B model;\n- a natural-language benchmark such as TRACE, ToolAlpaca, or knowledge injection;\n- per-task backward transfer and average forgetting;\n- KL drift from the pre-adaptation checkpoint;\n- a true SDFT implementation using the demonstration-conditioned teacher distribution;\n- GRPO or REINFORCE when an explicit verifier is available.\n\nThe small experiment is intended to find the boundary cheaply. It is not sufficient by itself to claim that the large-model result fails.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"7613a76d","cell_type":"code","source":"\n# Save an easy-to-share experiment manifest.\nmanifest = {\n    \"model_id\": MODEL_ID,\n    \"seed\": SEED,\n    \"rounds\": ROUNDS,\n    \"samples_per_prompt\": SAMPLES_PER_PROMPT,\n    \"learning_rate\": LEARNING_RATE,\n    \"batch_size\": BATCH_SIZE,\n    \"gradient_accumulation\": GRAD_ACCUM,\n    \"scenarios\": [\"supported\", \"novel\", \"conflict\"],\n    \"methods\": [\"offline_sft\", \"iterative_on_policy\", \"mixed\"],\n}\nwith open(WORKDIR / \"manifest.json\", \"w\") as f:\n    json.dump(manifest, f, indent=2)\nprint(\"Outputs:\", list(WORKDIR.iterdir()))\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-07-20T17:18:32.890996Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-07-20T17:18:32.89142Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-07-20T17:18:32.898778Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-07-20T17:18:32.891392Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-07-20T17:18:32.897805Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Outputs: [PosixPath('/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test/novel_iterative_on_policy_2'), PosixPath('/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test/novel_offline_sft_3'), PosixPath('/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test/supported_offline_sft_1'), PosixPath('/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test/novel_iterative_on_policy_1'), PosixPath('/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test/supported_offline_sft_3'), PosixPath('/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test/novel_iterative_on_policy_4'), PosixPath('/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test/novel_offline_sft_1'), PosixPath('/kaggle/working/on_policy_cl_stress_test/supported_iterative_on_policy_